A total of 6,271 candidates are sitting for the National Form Six Examinations in Kagera region with latest reports indicating that the exams are being conducted in conducive and safe environment. Kagera Regional Education Officer (REO), Mr Khalifa Shemahonge said that, of 6,271 candidates, 3,999 are male and 2,272 females. "The Form Six examinations are crucial for evaluating students' ability on their two years advanced secondary education as they prepare to join higher learning institutions to be shaped into professionals in various fields," he said. The assessment of the candidates for the Advanced Certificateof Secondary Education Examination (ACSEE) and teaching courses are scheduled from May 9 to 27, this year. National  Examinations Council of Tanzania  (NECTA)   Executive Director,  Dr Charles Msonde  explained that National Form Six examinations  began on Monday  across the country, with an increase  in  the number  of candidates  from  90,025 registered last year to  85,955 candidates  this year, which is equivalent to 6.6 per cent increase. On the other hand a total of 9,670 candidates are sitting for certificate and diploma examinations in teaching courses. Dr Msonde stated that the examinations for teaching courses are important in determining the competency of applicants who are intending to become teachers for primary and secondary schools. He warned owners of private examination centres to avoid meddling, stressing that the National Examinations Council of Tanzania (NECTA) will not hesitate to revoke the licence of centres which will violate guidelines set by the council.